7.0 Introduction to SharePoint Development

SharePoint development is divided into four categories:

1. Client-Side Development

SPFx (SharePoint Framework) â†’ Modern development method

JavaScript/TypeScript

React, Node.js, Graph API


2. Server-Side Development (Classic)

Farm solutions

Full trust code

C#, .NET
(Used only in on-premises SharePoint)


3. Low-Code Development

PowerApps

Power Automate

Power Pages

List form customization


4. API-Based Development

REST API

Microsoft Graph

Webhooks

CSOM (Client-Side Object Model)



---

7.1 SharePoint Framework (SPFx)

SPFx is the official development model for SharePoint Online.

7.1.1 Features of SPFx

100% client-side (no server code)

Uses:
âœ” React
âœ” TypeScript
âœ” Node.js
âœ” Webpack

Supports:
âœ” Web parts
âœ” Extensions
âœ” Application customizers
âœ” Command sets
âœ” Field customizers



---

7.2 SPFx Project Structure

A typical SPFx project contains:

config/             â†’ Build & bundle configs
node_modules/       â†’ Dependencies
src/
  webparts/
    <yourWebPart>/
      <Component>.tsx
      <WebPart>.ts
package.json        â†’ Dependencies
gulpfile.js         â†’ Tasks

Important Files

File	Purpose

package.json	Lists npm packages
gulpfile.js	Build commands
serve.json	Local testing config
manifest.json	Web part metadata



---

7.3 SPFx Web Parts

Types

1. React Web Parts â†’ most used


2. Non-React Web Parts â†’ simple JS


3. Adaptive Card Extensions (ACEs) â†’ Viva Connections



Capabilities

Connect to SharePoint lists

Display dashboards

Fetch data using REST or Graph

Create Tiles, Charts, Cards

Provide customization options (Property Pane)



---

7.4 SPFx Extensions

1. Application Customizer

Inject scripts into pages

Add footers/headers

Add chatbots, notifications


2. Field Customizer

Change column UI in a list

Example: status badges, icons


3. Command Set

Add custom buttons to list toolbars

Example: â€œApproveâ€, â€œRejectâ€, â€œSend Emailâ€



---

